data: {"type":"response.output_text.done","sequence_number":450,"item_id":"msg_09de98c919e27aa600693b373299ac8196b990d1f108193b22","output_index":4,"content_index":0,"text":"Could you clarify what you mean by \"secondary agent\" (what system or domain)? Below are common meanings and typical capabilities so you can see which fits your case.\n\nIf you mean a secondary agent in a multi-agent or distributed system, it usually provides:\n- Redundancy & failover: becomes active if the primary fails, ensuring high availability.\n- Replication & state sync: keeps a copy of state/data so it can take over quickly.\n- Health monitoring and heartbeats: watches primary and triggers failover on problems.\n- Load balancing / read-scaling: handles some workload (e.g., read-only requests) to reduce primary load.\n- Backups and recovery tasks: performs periodic backups and recovery testing.\n- Logging, auditing, and diagnostics: collects metrics and traces for troubleshooting.\n- Security controls / access filtering: enforces policies or handles sensitive checks separate from primary.\n- Graceful degradation: offers reduced functionality when primary or other services are degraded.\n\nIf you mean a secondary (assistant) agent in an AI or conversational architecture, it often:\n- Verifies or fact-checks outputs from the primary for correctness/safety.\n- Performs retrieval (search) and supplies evidence or sources.\n- Handles specialized sub-tasks (e.g., math, code execution, document parsing).\n- Sanitizes or filters content for policy or privacy concerns.\n- Acts as a “critic” that scores and ranks candidate responses.\n- Handles escalation or clarification: asks targeted follow-ups when the primary is uncertain.\n- Manages memory and user-specific context (personalization).\n\nDesign considerations / best practices:\n- Clear responsibilities and APIs so roles don’t overlap confusingly.\n- Fast and reliable state synchronization; idempotent operations for safe retry.\n- Health checks, timeouts, and well-defined failover triggers.\n- Least privilege security boundaries between agents.\n- Observability (logs, metrics) so you can diagnose who did what.\n- Graceful fallback behaviors to avoid oscillation between agents.\n\nIf you tell me the specific domain (web service, database cluster, customer-support bots, AI assistant stack, IoT, etc.), I’ll give a tailored list of responsibilities, examples, and configuration advice.","logprobs":[]}

